 ledger balanced by a careful hand, and the channel calms as if a fever has broken. The Breath-Thief hisses and hangs back from the binding, tasting no fear to glut itself upon, and it leaves a slick trail of lantern oil that gutters in honest wind. The Fen Queen nods once like a judge whose verdict matches her private hope, and she declares the apology properly made with offerings fitting the deed, neither more nor less. Rogan keeps his lungs strong and his throat clear, but the Queen marks his promise with a knotted reed-loop around his wrist that will tighten at the next still water as a reminder that debts do not evaporate, they condense. The envoy’s voice returns steadier than a market bell, the elders of Whisper Fen reopen their medicine baskets without haggling, and word reaches Marrowhold that shipments will move again as long as the city keeps its own words straight.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C3\", \"title\": \"Cut the Lantern and Strike the Parasite Hard\", \"text\": \"Rogan takes one look at the glimmering mimic light and decides that lies pampered become law, and he will not let that happen to a city already on a dry edge. He steps forward with the Storm-Skim sabre held low and snaps the wind-kelp rope around his waist so Nyssar can drag him back if the water tries to teach him humility. The fulgurite blade bites the lantern’s skin with a blue-white lick, and where the light spills the hymn screams in three stolen voices at once, a mother’s call, a lover’s tease, a commander’s bark, each prettier than truth. He does not stop, because he knows stopping breeds regret, and he carves a path through mimicry while shouting the names of the children he once saved to keep himself oriented toward what matters. When the parasite tries to take his breath by force, he gives it the sabre’s static taste instead and lets the blade sing the last word.\", \"outcome\": \"The parasite splits and flees into deeper channels, leaving the glass ampule bobbing amid a ribbon of gu